tThe City and the Park in Times of Pandemic: Children’s Practices in Public Spaces Before and After the Lockdown in Porto, Portugal -- tThe Mundane and (Extra)Ordinary Public Spaces in India: Examining the Impact of the COVID-19 Pandemic Through an Everyday Lens in Chennai City -- tThe Resilience of Street Vendors in Surviving the COVID-19 Crisis in Hanoi, Vietnam -- tPublic Space and Mobility -- tCity Cycling after COVID-19 for Interspecies Mobility Justice -- tMobility Justice and Social Inequality During the COVID-19 Pandemic in Jakarta -- tPandemic- and Future-Proofing Cities: Pedestrian-oriented Development as an Alternative Model to Transit-based Intensification Centers -- tMercurial Images of the COVID-19 City -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCOVID-19 is an invisible threat that has hugely impacted cities and their inhabitants. Yet its impact is very visible, perhaps most so in urban public spaces and spaces of mobility. This international volume explores the transformations of public space and public transport in response to COVID-19 across the world, both those resulting from official governmental regulations and from everyday practices of urban citizens. The contributors discuss how the virus made urban inequalities sharper and clearer, and redefined public spaces in the ‘new normal’. Offering crucial insights for reforming cities to be more resilient to future crises, this is an invaluable resource for scholars and policy makers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xSocial aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspects. 0aCities and townsxSocial aspects. 0aCity planning. 0aEquality. 0aPublic spaces. 0aUrban transportation.